he elegance and precision of Einstein's thought. Presented here is a beautiful facsimile of Einstein's original handwritten manuscript, along with its English translation and an insightful page-by-page commentary that places the work in historical and scientific context. Hanoch Gutfreund and Jürgen Renn's concise introduction traces Einstein's intellectual odyssey from special to general relativity, and their essay "The Charm of a Manuscript" provides a delightful meditation on the varied afterlife of Einstein's text. Featuring a foreword by John Stachel, this handsome edition also includes a biographical glossary of the figures discussed in the book, a comprehensive bibliography, suggestions for further reading, and numerous photos and illustrations throughout.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aGeneral relativity (Physics)xHistoryx20th century. 0aGeneral relativity (Physics)xHistoryy20th century. 7aSCIENCE / Physics / Relativity.2bisacsh  aAlbert Einstein Archives.  aAlbert Einstein.  aAnnalen der Physik.  aDavid Hilbert.  aEinstein-Besso manuscript.  aEinstein-Grossmann Entwurf paper.  aEntwurf theory.  aHebrew University.  aHeinrich Loewe.  aIsaac Newton.  aSchwarzschild solution.  aThe Foundation of General Relativity.  aWilhelm Wien.  aZurich Notebook.  aabsolute space.  aastronomy.  ablack holes.  acoordinates.  acosmology.  aequations of motion.  aequivalence principle.  ageneral theory of relativity.  agravitational field.  aheuristics.  alaws of conservation.  amanuscript.  aphysics.  arods.  aspacetime.  aspecial relativity.  aspecial theory of relativity.  atensors.  atheory of gravitation.1 aRenn, Jürgen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aStachel, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel